==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|assiduus|lang=la}}, from {{term|assidere||to sit down to|lang=la}}, from {{term|ad-||to|lang=la}} + {{term|sedere||to sit|lang=la}}.<ref name="OEtD">{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>

Cognate (via ''assidere'') to {{term|assess|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əˈsɪdʒ.jʊ.əs/}} {{SAMPA|/@"sIdZ.jU.@s/}}
* {{audio|en-us-assiduous.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# [[hard-working|Hard-working]], [[diligent]] or [[regular]] (in attendance or work); [[industrious]].
#* '''1831''', [[w:Sir Walter Scott|Sir Walter Scott]], ''The Surgeon's Daughter'', ch. 2:
#*: He was officious in the right time and place, quiet as a lamb when his patron seemed inclined to study or to muse, active and '''assiduous''' to assist or divert him whenever it seemed to be wished.

====Usage notes====
* Since the 19th century, this terms has sometimes carried connotations of servility.<ref name="OEtD" />

====Synonyms====
* [[meticulous]], [[diligent]], [[sedulous]]
* See also [[Wikisaurus:industrious]]

